The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech service providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting for him for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers are the most expensive in Europe, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the ČTù telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price of a text message is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some of the Czech mobile service providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight announcement.
It may sound paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTù) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, he would probably not find any frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators also had to respond.
Before the entry of such companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market in the UK, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February, we reported on the start of the virtual mobile provider in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus to become the country's fifth largest provider.
The Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic has, among other things, U: fon, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually benefit as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but this is often accompanied by a less comprehensive service offer.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobile learning in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to set a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically directed at men.
"Real guys choose mobile - the provider that they like and that they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could take a foot in the Czech Republic as in Poland.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer. "
In the Czech Republic, the mobile telephone operators mean without a chance
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobile.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
There will be more of a market entry of mobile telephony in other countries of our region, "says in a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile service provider has been shown for a long time by the group GTS Novera, which wants to take a further step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of company customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in the negotiations, "said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe we'll have better times.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an invincible wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area, "says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specific market in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare terms with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "In the network of T-Mobile hardly any virtual provider will appear until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have a concrete offer to be able to think so in the short term. "
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we consider to be the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet. "
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competitive, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
That the providers can pull on a line when it comes to something, also the long move and get over the formation of U: fon.
The most powerful pressure in the direction of ČTùwas at the time when U: fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidence of the publicly available information from the ČTù websites.
But now you: fon is the argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competition of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile telephone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would make high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services. "
However, in view of this approach by mobile telephone providers, the Czech regulatory authorities' absolute disinterest is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTù, which unfortunately does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries.
This is the sole responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile operator would be possible after a contract was concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers, "said Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our question.
Such a formulation would not be surprised by the representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one uses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work in a normal way, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost touching agreement of the three mobile telephone providers, which is the result of their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely same fuel price at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"In this case, the Authority has not found any evidence to suggest any action against competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so it does not have the appropriate increased responsibility for its action on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulatory authority, "said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by ČTù, where telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the mobile phone provider, logically, has the monopoly for his network.
This means that it is necessarily dominant in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile telephone providers are acting remarkably similar.
In this respect, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the GTS Novera mentioned company) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTù is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS dissociates from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent revision of the telecommunications law has not been able to enforce the extension of ČTù 's powers to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay when no one looks
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
For example, own mobile telephone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to the chosen ones.
The joke is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company that orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile telephone providers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a breach of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which can lead to an end to the cooperation with the relevant society," said Martina Kemrová on our question.
It is, however, quite unlikely that such a thing will not speak about with those responsible for the mobile telephone providers.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an approach.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not give them negligible profits, but, in contrast to the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite the fact that the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of the customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card does not run on their name in their phone, so they cannot fully possess it like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers. "
But this alone would at least have to be strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Do the mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the supplier's statement that they do not know about it and that their terms of business would prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers has led to a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In practice, in all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their development from being virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - an too small, or too saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies in particular intervened in these moments, which were not trying to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
If it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the lack of clarity in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the gun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make more calls than the rest of Europe.
