The Prague transport companies also carry on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will enter the history of the Prague transport companies as a date on which the first passengers to carry an electronic coupon in their pocket will enter a subway, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
The passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can also play it on their chip card, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylly, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available on the Internet on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used up to the afternoon hours of over four hundred customers.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have so far had to wait regularly in long snakes for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places, a switch with trained staff is also available to the traveller, who advises interested parties to buy the Internet and also plays the coupon on the map," said the speaker of the Martin Opatrný project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on self-service machines on the Opencard, which are installed in some subway vestibüls.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, remind of the ticket value, passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work from tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon will be on its own.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburbs and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia, in particular, enter the capital.
"In the trains that are part of the Prague integrated traffic, the train crew readers are able to check the validity of the coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation. This organisation is the one that sets up the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card reading equipment at the register with the driver.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the opencard must be placed at a marked place at the side of the register.
In this way the driver controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the recorded coupons, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," said Drápal.
