"We cannot believe that, without regard to the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are to address a foreign state that is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has done nothing to the victory of the Allies," is to be read in the letter.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors."
If the President of the United States had doubts about the thinking of the Böhmerwalddeutsche, it would be sufficient if he were to initiate a referendum in the Böhmerwaldgau on whether the inhabitants would become part of the United States or to live under the protection of the United States.
