Although the Bohemian Germans at least had to know that they would be negotiating their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them agreed to such an opportunity at all.
Some were waiting for the United States and the United Kingdom to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeds.
Others again believed that they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
