Discussion - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most secure and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has recovered the public's trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were infected with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the light of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation in February 1994, led by the Judge Horace Kever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Kever was still reluctant to report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the management of blood reserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Kever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
In 1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, almost 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conserve system in Quebec, Dr. Décary remembers.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood reserves and by working in this area in the following years, we have recovered public confidence ', she says, before she proudly stresses that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of many cases of the human form of bovine disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation of 1998.
'And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we were looking at one of the main guidelines of the reports of Kever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied, if one does not know this and if a disease only slowly progresses, as is clearly the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
This event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise technology for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the donor to prove the presence of the virus directly in the blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it and not being able to recognize it was significantly reduced.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmission of AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood infected with HIV.
In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million blood reserves before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transmitted via a blood conserve.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health, "says the director of Hema-Quebec.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogens can get into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus was found on the island of Réunion, which, just like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously ', Dr. Décary continues before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient care in addition to a safe supply.
"The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of the population of Quebec that is suitable for blood donation. '
In doing so, any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the criteria of suitability can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who make their blood available are not accepted, for example because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from the blood donation for one year.
'With these 3%, we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
The lack of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can't donate blood anymore.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and to make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that one rarely finds the time to spend an hour in the donation of blood ', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood conserve, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart flaps, eyelashes and skin, which is used almost exclusively in severe burns.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public nebula blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was previously considered a biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousands of umbilical blood samples, and we plan to take over a thousand a year.
"We should probably start at the beginning of next year to provide it for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical blood collection as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it ', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals in Quebec.
