The psychology of overbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overassess the offer.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give up in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even overpriced prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lotto, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were studied by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to gain money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain bark, was measured in the case of the auction losers, in which the overoffering of the opponent plays a significant role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out research into the follow-up of the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they were the winner of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis was on the one on the winning, while the other was on the losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were prepared to do more than those in the control or "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have, in fact, only been the reasons for the behaviour observed in auctions with the joy of winning or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready - "said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the University of New York's Economic Faculty.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in the country is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, the liver viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as semen, paraphermal secretion or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two-three weeks after the consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and rashes.
After that, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B-induced, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected person is in medicinal treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it may lead to cirrhosis of the liver and cancer of the liver.
Most of the infected do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destructs the liver cells inadvertently - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, prevention, such as regular control tests, is essential in time.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
As the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, which will eliminate the risk of infection and prevent the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time organised by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver infection caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
Are believers less in pain?
As the latest research shows, religious faith is like a kind of "painkillers," which should have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: it has been examined to what extent faith in God affects the sense of pain of man, the British sheet "Telegraph."
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks, while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers were able to take out most of the pain.
With the help of a brain scan technology, it was even possible to prove that the Catholics could activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
When the test was done, the subjects were connected to the left hand with a sparkling device that gave off the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would create a kind of religious trance among the believers, while they chose the image of Vincent, because it was hardly different from the other painting and was considered to be calming.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and during that time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they should look at either the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for," and they had felt "peace and peace."
During the consideration of the religious painting, they reported more than 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the attempt, said that you could also produce similar effects with other, strong-acting images with the atheists, you just had to find the appropriate photo.
"We need to find a picture that makes very positive sensations, like a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases," Wright said.
According to these excellent results, only the question remains which effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another similar painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
