One possible reason for this is that Google does not require any identification codes to its users, unlike Microsoft, and makes its services available free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems to be far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks are looking through the problem of the relationship between personal rights and the Internet, a relationship that has been at the centre of the process, especially in recent years, thanks to the term "Web 2.0."
In fact, the "Web 2.0" is about nothing but collaboration, that is, users are deliberately leaving traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show themselves publicly.
An average young person can manage his profile at the same time on several community sports - from Facebook via Xanga, it can connect with each other by means of other services such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can finally include all this in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can lead blogs that are the latest photo galleries that are automatically located on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove that, when looking at the party photos of last night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend was having fun with, or the employee is being released because in his blog he is only too honest about his problems about corporate management - one thing is certain: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Those who live an online life are what they reveal of themselves - so one could perhaps formulate the basic idea behind the behaviour of today's youth.
And who tries to keep something secret, or even to bypass the Google monopoly, can do so - like with Scroogle, a tool that, while accessing Google's search engine, does not intentionally leave any trace.
Not a few people deliberately do not register on community pages so that they are not found, but also the online applications of Google, such as text processing and graphic tools and RSS feeds, can be used with alternative versions that are not connected to huge server parks and therefore do not generate the best possible profile from the user.
However, public opinion is waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), the advertising areas of AdWords / AdSense are threatening the revenues of the advertising agencies, and the more and more rapidly introduced services are not only preparing Microsoft, but also other software developers.
