Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents, if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan an amazing project was presented, which inspired the Nissan engineers of humming in the creation of new accident prevention systems.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C-type biomimetic system, which is controlled by car robots, a mini-car, equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private" area, which is very similar to our own "protection shield," Kazuhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a 180-degree field within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately starts the conflict-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in seconds of break, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tyres around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If not, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered to be inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to be in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, the evisceration cannot go down, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the weatherability of the tyres.
While the bees are here infinitely open to the possibility of avoiding other bees, the researchers could only use the motion of the car, or the acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh said that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device must only process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It doesn't have to save it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous maneuvers, so that it always only uses a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate conflict prevention technology, which Nissan is estimated to be in production as standard over the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the drivers around obstacles and leading them to the goal.
