Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office, is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both in the public administration and in the public administration.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office now presents itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now sparsely designed initial menu, a basic compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system is finally achieved, as well as the support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, which is the latest standard ISO version.
Eight against was also the compatibility with Microsoft's Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Some new features are also interesting, such as those that allow to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which, for example, facilitates sending via email. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics processing modules while maintaining the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can be generated, which extend the typical graphics of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a text processing system.
The cooperation is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed by several users, thus avoiding conflicts in the case of changes; in the case of the text processing system, a question is assigned to each processor in order to ensure a better correction procedure.
Some companies are in the process of publishing various OpenOffice functions on the Internet (on the cloud), while in the coming weeks the final result will be published.
The Italian version is available on the following link to the download: http: / / it.openoffice.org / download / 3.0.0 / download300.html.
The program is also available for the Linux operating system, except for Windows and Mac OS.
On request you can send the installation CD home or to the office.
However, the free movement of costs may be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, so it is also in the area of business, where OpenOffice could succeed in the great throw: after all, various public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, it does not even lack a training offer, which means an optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice is composed of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text setting program; Calc, the table program, which aims to repress Excel; Impress, to create presentations such as PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more well-known access; and last but not least, draw, a graphics module.
The target for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads - a target that can be slightly exceeded at already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
