Students victims of high rental prices of up to 900-Euro per room
The market for apartments for students has no crises.
According to the last study of the Sunia, the tenants' union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious traits. In fact, a large number of students lose their right to study, as their families are not able to support them at this level" - the people responsible for Sunia, Laura Mariani - "in these cities, the great demand of the students leads to a deformation of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most of the rental offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, lack of registration, without a rental price limit, unauthorized underrental.
For the Sunia there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices by a revision of the tax.
With a closer look at the study, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping area in the Brianza district is needed about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district, or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a sleeping area costs an average of 350 / 400 euros, one room 700.
In Bologna, where the students concentrate in the districts around the university, 250 / 280 euros are for a sleeping area of need, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, the prices in the quarters around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping area in a double room.
Only a little deeper are the rents in the quarters around the other universities of Rome: 550 Euro in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who evade the area can save money: 300 euros for a place to sleep and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centokelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for one room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive quarters, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a bed is 250-350 Euro, a single room at least 350 Euro.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they are more important in the urban economy.
In the cities in which the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rental that is 25-30% higher than the average is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso - the cities close their historical cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the beneficiary multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the great urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of the cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multilanguage complex in the periphery, means in the long term death for the Einsaalkino in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also bears the traits of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom one has made a piece of road full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a world that is probably forever lost.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the huge amount of 316 traditional cinemas have been closed; these mines paid for the most part the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main guilty are the multiplexkinos, because it is these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has been leading the lists, 81 are in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, the President of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are also emerging, but the first thing is to maintain the already existing, because it closes a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplexcinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the missing budget for the trade union fund remains out of the question: the government's debt burden is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between EUR 16 and 18 million a year would be of need. "
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinema halls, has decided to protect it by an agreement between the community and the Anec, is the first such agreement in Italy to protect and support the traditional cinema, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are also tax advantages for cinema operators and benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to go to the traffic-sensitive areas of the centre and to park at more favourable parking charges.
"It is a welcome initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
But certainly we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiple rooms, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of the traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "supercinema" of Bagiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that made me start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso," even though I had played with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; if I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to not have to see the dust-covered posters.
