When the energy comes out of the waves, the great ones suddenly run up
It is an unbeatable source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface and only now it seems that the great energy companies in the world understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that all now look at, and also seek to occupate, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and examined for 70 years, and these studies have not happened to be significantly intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gas, but now the environmental organisations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would also come.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in the north of Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, it is now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry that are relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies" - the spokesperson of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal - and is considering the possibility of working with us. "
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that is not to be underestimated, especially given that in Alaska, oil is still being promoted by the US and President Bush has just launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are not known, but observers are talking about an increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still emerging, not least because the last doubts have not yet been resolved by the environmental protection authorities.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and also Scotland have a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it is necessary to have a much greater impact on the environment.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power uses a system of connected bojen for example.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the bojen up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmers via flasks and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn runs a generator.
The current is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval, and part of the energy obtained could also be used for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using subsea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotation.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorisations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Recovery Research, a special interest deserves the potential that is in the tides at the moment.
Although it is an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, the sun's radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is precisely the tidal energy that led states like New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 - up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
